    <h1>Oren Shoham's ITP Creative Portfolio</h1>

    <section id="pixel-study">
      <h2 class="itp-portfolio__section-title">Pixel Study</h2>
      <p class="itp-portfolio__section-description">
        <i>Pixel Study</i> is an interactive installation that explores different ways of rendering the pixels of a webcam, drawing inspiration from vector graphics, ASCII art, and mosaics. It is comprised of an openFrameworks app that manipulates webcam video in real time, and a physical interface powered by an Arduino microcontroller that controls parameters that drive the behavior of the installation. The intent of the interface is to allow the viewer to gain insight into the computational systems that they are interacting with through experimentation and feedback. <i>Pixel Study</i> was made as my final project for the 2016 Summer session of the School for Poetic Computation.
      </p>

      <video class="itp-portfolio__project-video" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/itp-portfolio/movies/2016-summer-sfpc-showcase.mp4" controls></video>
    </section>

    <section id="bike-synth">
      <h2 class="itp-portfolio__section-title">Bike Wheel Looper</h2>
      <p class="itp-portfolio__section-description">
        A looping sample-based instrument made using a bike wheel, mechanical switches, an Arduino running <a href="http://www.arduino.cc/en/Reference/Firmata" target="_blank">Firmata</a>, and an <a href="http://openframeworks.cc/" target="_blank">openFrameworks</a> app. Collaboration with <a href="http://mattvis.co/" target="_blank">Matt Visco</a> and <a href="http://sfpc.io/people/krista-nordgren/" target="_blank">Krista Nordgren</a>.
      </p>

      <video class="itp-portfolio__project-video" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/itp-portfolio/movies/bike_synth.mp4" controls></video>
    </section>


    <section id="turbines">
      <h2 class="itp-portfolio__section-title">Turbines</h2>
      <p class="itp-portfolio__section-description">
        A series of animations inspired by the helical motion of <a href="http://youtu.be/Q5COAi6KM8o?t=14s" target="_blank">smoke from a wind turbine on fire</a>. Made with <a href="http://openframeworks.cc/" target="_blank">openFrameworks</a>. Because openFrameworks apps are difficult to share on the web, I have created a short video for each piece. A link to the source code can be found underneath each video.
      </p>

      <div class="itp-portfolio__sketches">
      <% for sketch in turbine_sketches %>
        <div class="itp-portfolio__sketch">
          <video class="itp-portfolio__sketch-video" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/itp-portfolio/movies/<%= sketch[:file_name] %>.mp4" poster="https://s3.amazonaws.com/itp-portfolio/images/<%= sketch[:file_name] %>.jpg" preload="none" controls loop muted></video>
          <a class="itp-portfolio__sketch-source-link" href="<%= sketch[:source_url] %>" target="_blank" title="View the source code">
            <img src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/itp-portfolio/images/GitHub-Mark-120px-plus.png" width="30" height="30">
          </a>
          <p class="itp-portfolio__sketch-description"><%= sketch[:description] %></p>
        </div>
      <% end %>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="recreating-the-past">
      <h2 class="itp-portfolio__section-title">Recreating the Past</h2>
      <p class="itp-portfolio__section-description">
       Creative coding works made for Zach Lieberman's class "Recreating the Past" at the School for Poetic Computation in the summer of 2016. Each piece is a response to an existing work of computational art. Some were made with <a href="http://openframeworks.cc/" target="_blank">openFrameworks</a>, others with <a href="http://p5js.org/" target="_blank">p5.js</a>.
      </p>

      <div class="itp-portfolio__sketches">
